    "recap_headline": "TCU",
    "recap_text": "FORT WORTH\n\u2013\nSawyer Strosnider's\nbig day at the plate keyed TCU's 16-6 victory over New Mexico State Tuesday afternoon at Lupton Stadium. The sophomore homered twice and drove in eight as part of a four-hit game.\nThe Rundown\nTCU scored in all six offensive innings, but had to rally as New Mexico State jumped out to a 5-1 lead.\nSawyer Strosnider's\ndouble in the first gave TCU a 1-0 lead, but the Aggies had a response in the second. Two home runs in the inning, including a grand slam, put New Mexico State on top.\nThe Frogs comeback started in the bottom of the second as it took advantage of an Aggie error to score three unearned runs.\nCole Cramer\ntripled home two runs and scored on a Strosnider base hit to make it a 5-4 ballgame.\nNew Mexico State homered again in the third, but the Frogs answered in the bottom of the frame to keep it a one-run ballgame. Two walks around a\nColton Griffin\nbase hit loaded the bases.\nJack Bell\nworked the bases-loaded free pass to make it a 6-5 contest.\nTCU completed the comeback in the fourth with a trio of runs. Walks again set the table for the Frogs. Griffin tied the game with a two-out single and\nLucas Franco\ngave the Frogs an 8-6 lead with a two-run base knock.\nStrosnider's two-run home run in the seventh extended the lead to 10-6. A six-spot followed in the sixth. Four walks started the inning and Bell drew his second bases-loaded walk of the game. Cramer followed with an RBI-single and Strosnider capped the scoring with a grand slam.\nThe bullpen trio of\nTyler Phenow\n,\nZack James\nand\nCade Nelson\ngave the Frogs 5 2/3 in relief of\nUli Fernsler\n. Phenow fanned two and allowed a run in 1 1/3 innings of work. James (3-0) threw two scoreless as did Nelson.\nStat of the Game:\n8 \u2013\nSawyer Strosnider\ndrove in eight runs in the contest. It's tied for the sixth-most RBIs in a single-game this season in the NCAA. It's the most by a Horned Frog since Tre Richardson drove in 11 against Arkansas on June 4, 2023.\nNotes:\n\u2022 TCU scored double-digit runs for the sixth time this season.\n\u2022 TCU tallied double-digit hits (10) for the sixth time this season.\n\u2022 TCU outhit its opponent for the sixth time this season.\n\u2022 TCU homered in a game for the 14\nth\ntime this season.\n\u2022 TCU hit multiple home runs in a game for the fifth time this season.\n\u2022 TCU drew double-digit walks (12) for the fourth time this season.\n\u2022 TCU registered a stolen base in a game for the 15\nth\ntime this season.\n\u2022 TCU scored seven two-out runs in the contest.\n\u2022 TCU played errorless baseball for the sixth time this season.\n\u2022 TCU turned one double play in the game.\n\u2022\nCole Cramer\ntallied his fourth multi-hit game of the season and the 43\nrd\nof his career.\n\u2022 Cramer registered his third multi-RBI game of the year and the 23\nrd\nof his career.\n\u2022\nSawyer Strosnider\nhas reached safely in 36 straight games dating back to last season.\n\u2022 Strosnider tallied his third career multi-home run game.\n\u2022 Strosnider hit his fifth and sixth home run of the season and now has 17 in his career.\n\u2022 Strosnider recorded his fourth multi-hit game of the year and the 27\nth\nof his career.\n\u2022 Strosnider posted his sixth multi-RBI game of the season and the 19\nth\nof his career.\n\u2022\nColton Griffin\nhas reached safely in 11 straight games.\n\u2022 Griffin notched his third multi-hit game of the season and the 25\nth\nof his career.\n\u2022\nJack Bell\ntallied his second multi-RBI game of the year and the 11\nth\nof his career.\nNext Up:\nWith the win, TCU improves to 12-8 on the season.\u00a0TCU will host league-leading UCF in a three game series starting Friday night. First pitch is set for 6 p.m. The game will be televised on ESPN+."
